2 K-Nearest Neighbors

In this exercise, I write codes of ‘k-nearest neighbors’ and classify titanic datasets focusing on ‘survived’ variable.

library(titanic)
library(tidyverse)

2.1 KNN Code

First, clean the datasets for data analysis. Randomly choose 70 % for the train set and 30 % for the test set.

Prepare a function for calculating euclidean distance between two observations.

euclideanDistv <- function(x, y){
  d <- sqrt(sum((x - y)^2))
  return(d)
}

Then, write a function named ‘knn’ that calculates euclidean distances between two points in the train set and the test set and returns predicted class labels of test data by counting labels of k neighbors.

knn <- function(test_data, train_data, k_value) {
  pred <- c()  #empty pred vector
  #LOOP-1
  for (i in c(1:nrow(test_data))) {
    eu_dist = c()
    eu_char = c()
    yes = 0
    no = 0
    
    #LOOP-2-looping over train data
    for (j in c(1:nrow(train_data))) {
      #adding euclidean distance between test data point and train data to eu_dist vector
      eu_dist <-
        c(eu_dist, euclideanDistv(test_data[i, -1], train_data[j, -1])) #remove the Y label (1st column in this case)
      #adding class variable of training data in eu_char
      eu_char <-
        c(eu_char, as.character(train_data[j, 1])) #where Y variable is
    }
    
    eu <-
      data.frame(eu_char, eu_dist) #eu dataframe created with eu_char & eu_dist columns
    eu <-
      eu[order(eu$eu_dist), ]       #sorting eu dataframe to find top K neighbors
    eu <-
      eu[1:k_value, ]               #eu dataframe with top K neighbors
    
    #Loop 3: loops over eu and counts classes of neighbors.
    for (k in c(1:nrow(eu))) {
      if (as.character(eu[k, "eu_char"]) == 1) {
        yes = yes + 1
      }
      else
        no = no + 1
    }
    
    # Compares the no. of neighbors with class label yes or no
    if (yes > no) {
      pred <- c(pred, 1)
    }
    else if (yes < no) {
      pred <- c(pred, 0)
    }
    
  }
  return(pred) #return pred vector
}

2.2 KNN Calculation

Create a function called accuracy that calculates how accurate the predictions are for the test labels.

accuracy <- function(test_data) {
  correct = 0
  for (i in c(1:nrow(test_data))) {
    if (test_data[i, 1] == test_data$prediction[i]) {
      #If correctly predicted labels
      correct = correct + 1                          #Add +1
    }
  }
  accu = correct / nrow(test_data) * 100  #calculate the ratio
  return(accu)
}

Using K=5, predict labels for the testing data using the knn function and analyze accuracy of the result.

predictions <- knn(tit_test, tit_train, 5)

Using the bivariate regression and a function, calculate the expected median value of housing price if RM = 6.28 (mean of the number of rooms).

predict_mine <- function(value, model){
  coef <- model$coefficients
  y <- unname(coef[1] + coef[2]*value)
  return (y)
}

predicted <- predict_mine(6.28, bivariate) 
print(predicted)
## [1] 22.49062

The expected value of housing price is 22.49 ($1,000’s).

Create a prediction function and predict the housing price using the multivariate regression.

multipredict_mine <- function(values, model){
  values <- c(1, values)
  if(length(values) != length(model$coefficients)) stop("!!!") # flag
   y <- values%*%unname(model$coefficients)
   return (y)
}

multi_prediction <- multipredict_mine(c(6.28, 1, 0.55, 3.8, 18.5), multivariate)
print(multi_prediction)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 26.24587

The expected value of housing price is now 26.25 ($1,000’s).

3.4 Bootstrap

We are often interested in characterizing the uncertainty in our estimates. One nonparametric approach to estimating uncertainty is the bootstrap. Here, I will walk through the steps to produce a function that will produce a bootstrap distribution, from which we can find the bootstrap estimates (and 95% confidence bands).

n <- 1000 # size of bootstrap

# creating empty vectors for results
bi_results <- rep(NA,n)
multi_results <- rep(NA,n)

for (i in 1:n){
  # create bootstrap data
  sim_data <- housing[sample(nrow(housing), 506, replace = TRUE), ] # number of observations
  
  # run bivariate and multivariate regressions using this data
  bi <- lm(MEDV ~ RM, data = sim_data)
  multi <- lm(MEDV ~ RM + CHAS + NOX + DIS + PTRATIO, data = sim_data)
  
  # use the functions to make predictions and store
  bi_results[i] <- predict_mine(6.28, bi)
  multi_results[i] <- multipredict_mine(c(6.28, 1, 0.55, 3.8, 18.5), multi)
}

# putting predictions in data frame for the next question
predicted_vals <- as.data.frame(cbind(bi_results, multi_results))

Create histograms for both predictions adding lines for the prediction and 95% confidence bands.

biplot <- ggplot(predicted_vals, aes(bi_results)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=50) +   
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(x= NULL, y = NULL, 
       title = "Predicted values from bivariate regressions")

biplot + 
  # prediction from Q3
  geom_vline(xintercept = predicted, linetype="solid", color = "skyblue1", size=1) +

  geom_vline(xintercept = sort(predicted_vals$bi_results)[round(0.025*nrow(predicted_vals),0)],

4.3 Fit LASSO Regression

Try to improve the result of the test datasets by using LASSO regression that is available in the glmnet library.

library(glmnet)
lasso <- glmnet(x = as.data.frame(train), y = train_label)

The LASSO function automatically fits the model for several values of \(\lambda\), and produces \(\beta\) values for all covariates for each value of \(\lambda\) all of which is found in the object lasso$beta.

Sum up the absolute values of lasso$beta for each column. Plot that against lasso$lambda.

# sum absolute values of the betas
sum_beta <- colSums(abs(lasso$beta))

# plot against values of lambda
plot(sum_beta ~ lasso$lambda, pch=16, col="dodgerblue1")

As \(\lambda\) increases, the number of \(\beta\) coefficients (and hence the sum) gets pushed down to 0, increasing regularization.

In this case, I set a particular value of lambda arbitrarily and then assess its performance. I will set lambda to 0.02.

Formulate predictions for the training set using the following syntax: lasso_pred <- predict(lasso, newx=train, s = 0.05 )

  • lasso is the lasso regression
  • newx are the values you want to predict
  • s is the value of lambda.

Classify the observations using a threshold of 0.5. Then assess the accuracy of those predictions by comparing them to the training set labels and create a confusion matrix.

# formulate predictions
lasso_pred <- predict(lasso, newx = train, s = 0.02)

# classify obs using threshold of 0.5
class_lasso1 <- ifelse(lasso_pred > 0.5, 1, 0)

# create confusion matrix
table(class_lasso1, train_label)
##             train_label
## class_lasso1   0   1
##            0 327   5
##            1   2 366
# get accuracy score
(sum(class_lasso1 & train_label) + sum(!class_lasso1 & !train_label)) / length(train_label)
## [1] 0.99
# classify obs using threshold with prior
class_lasso2 <- ifelse(lasso_pred > sum(train_label)/length(train_label), 1, 0)

# create confusion matrix
table(class_lasso2, train_label)
##             train_label
## class_lasso2   0   1
##            0 327   7
##            1   2 364
# get accuracy score
(sum(class_lasso2 & train_label) + sum(!class_lasso2 & !train_label)) / length(train_label)
## [1] 0.9871429

Notice that I don’t have the perfect in-sample fit that I had before. It means that I am not overfitting the data.

Lastly, compare accuracies by setting different lambdas.

lambda <- seq(0, 0.1, len = 30)
acc <- rep(NA, 30)
for (i in c(1:30)) {
    lasso_test <- predict(lasso, newx = test, s = lambda[i])
    class_lasso_test <-
      ifelse(lasso_test > sum(test_label) / length(test_label),
             1,

      (
        sum(class_lasso_test &
              test_label) + sum(!class_lasso_test &
                                       !test_label)
      ) / length(test_label)
    acc[i] <- lasso_acc
  }
plot(lambda, acc)

5.2 Ridge Regression

The glmnet() function has an alpha argument that determines what type of model is fit. If alpha = 0 then a ridge regression model is fit, and if alpha = 1 then a lasso model is fit.

grid = 10^seq(10, -2, length = 100)
ridge_mod = glmnet(data, label, alpha = 0, lambda = grid) # alpha = 0 means `ridge`

By default the glmnet() function performs ridge regression for an automatically selected range of \(\lambda\) values. However, here I have chosen to implement the function over a grid of values ranging from \(\lambda = 10^{10}\) to \(\lambda = 10^{-2}\), essentially covering the full range of scenarios from the null model containing only the intercept, to the least squares fit.

Associated with each value of \(\lambda\) is a vector of ridge regression coefficients, stored in a matrix that can be accessed by coef(). In this case, it is a \(12 \times 100\) matrix, with 12 rows (one for each predictor, plus an intercept) and 100 columns (one for each value of \(\lambda\)).

dim(coef(ridge_mod))
## [1]  12 100
plot(ridge_mod, label = TRUE)

I expect the coefficient estimates to be much smaller, in terms of \(l_2\) norm, when a large value of \(\lambda\) is used, as compared to when a small value of \(\lambda\) is used.

ridge_mod$lambda[50] # Display 50th lambda value

7.2 Forward Propagation

Write a forward propagation function (I use the sigmoid function for the activation). The function takes x, w1 and w2 as arguments and output the sigmoid of z2 and h (sigmoid of z1).

sigmoid <- function(x) 1 / (1 + exp(-x)) # prepare sigmoid function

# Forward propagation function
feedforward <- function(x, w1, w2) {
  # Compute linear combination of features using weight matrix (W_in)
  z1 <- cbind(1, x) %*% w1 
  # Apply activation fn to get nodes in hidden layer
  h <- sigmoid(z1)
  # For output layer, compute linear combination of hidden variables, this time using another weight matrix (W_out)
  z2 <- cbind(1, h) %*% w2
  # Apply one more function to get the output
  output <- sigmoid(z2)
  return(list(output = output, 
              h = h))
}

7.3 Back Propagation

Write a back propagation function. The function takes as arguments: x, y, yhat, w1, w2, h, and the learning rate. It should return a list with w1 and w2.

# Back propagation function
backpropagate <- function(x, y, y_hat, w1, w2, h, learn_rate) {
  # Gradient of the log-likelihood w.r.t the output weights (W_out)
  dw2 <- t(cbind(1, h)) %*% (y_hat - y)
  # Gradient of the log-likelihood w.r.t the input weights (W_in)
  dh  <- (y_hat - y) %*% t(w2[-1, , drop = FALSE]) # n by h matrix
  # When drop is FALSE, the dimensions of the object are kept
  dw1 <- t(cbind(1, x)) %*% (h * (1 - h) * dh) # (d+1) by h matrix
  
  w1 <- w1 - learn_rate * dw1
  w2 <- w2 - learn_rate * dw2
  
  list(w1 = w1, w2 = w2)
}

7.4 Train the Network

Write a training function for your neural network. It takes as arguments, x, y, the number of hidden nodes, the learning rate (set as default 1e-2), and the number of iterations (set default at 1e3). Return the final forward feeding output, w1 and w2.

# Training function
train.nn <- function(x, y, hidden = 1, learn_rate = 1e-2, iterations = 1e3) {
  # Initialize weights
  dp1 <- ncol(x) + 1 # d+1
  w1 <- matrix(rnorm(dp1 * hidden), dp1, hidden)
  w2 <- as.matrix(rnorm(hidden + 1))
  for (i in 1:iterations) { # 2. Iterate forward and back propagation:
    # Propagate forward to get output estimate
    ff <- feedforward(x, w1, w2)
    # Propagate error backwards to update the weights towards a better solution
    bp <- backpropagate(x, y,
                        y_hat = ff$output,
                        w1, w2,
                        h = ff$h,
                        learn_rate = learn_rate)
    w1 <- bp$w1; w2 <- bp$w2
  }
  ff <- feedforward(x, w1, w2) # final forward feeding output
  
  list(output = ff$output, w1 = w1, w2 = w2)
}

Train my neural network with 1 hidden nodes on the data. Calculate the number of objects it classifies correctly using the 0.5 cutoff.

nnet1 <- train.nn(x, y, hidden = 1, iterations = 1e3)
acc_1 <- mean((nnet1$output > .5) == y)

8.1 Maximal Margin Classifier

If the classes are separable by a linear boundary, we can use a Maximal Margin Classifier to find the classification boundary. To visualize an example of separated data, generate 40 random observations and assign them to two classes.

Upon visual inspection, I can see that infinitely many lines exist that split the two classes. Below, I draw two example classification boundaries, and draw line segments from each observation to the boundary lines. The goal of the maximal margin classifier is to identify the linear boundary that maximizes the total distance between the line and the closest point in each class.

set.seed(2022)

# Construct sample data set - completely separated
x <- matrix(rnorm(20*2), ncol = 2)
y <- c(rep(-1,10), rep(1,10))
x[y==1,] <- x[y==1,] + 3L
dat <- data.frame(x=x, y=as.factor(y))

# Plot data
ggplot(data = dat, aes(x = x.2, y = x.1, color = y)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#000000", "#FF0000")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_abline(intercept = 2.0, slope = -1, color = "green", 
                 linetype = "dashed", size = 1) + # example classification boundary 1
  geom_abline(intercept = 6.0, slope = -5, color = "blue", # example classification boundary 2
                 linetype = "dashed", size = 1)

# Draw perpenticular lines to the boundary lines
perp.segment.coord <- function(x0, y0, a=0, b=1){
 # finds endpoint for a perpendicular segment from the point (x0,y0) to the line (x1, y1)
  x1 <- (x0+b*y0-a*b)/(1+b^2)
  y1 <- a + b*x1
  list(x0=x0, y0=y0, x1=x1, y1=y1)
}

ss1 <- perp.segment.coord(dat$x.2, dat$x.1, 2.0, -1)
ss2 <- perp.segment.coord(dat$x.2, dat$x.1, 6.0, -5)

ggplot(data = dat, aes(x = x.2, y = x.1, color = y)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#000000", "#FF0000")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_abline(intercept = 2.0, slope = -1, color = "green", 
                 linetype = "dashed", size = 1) + # example classification boundary 1
  geom_abline(intercept = 6.0, slope = -5, color = "blue", # example classification boundary 2
                 linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  geom_segment(data=as.data.frame(ss1), aes(x = x0, y = y0, xend = x1, yend = y1), colour = "green") +
  geom_segment(data=as.data.frame(ss2), aes(x = x0, y = y0, xend = x1, yend = y1), colour = "blue")

Now, use the svm() function in the e1071 package to find the linear boundary that maximizes the distance.

# Fit Support Vector Machine model to data set
svmfit <- svm(y~., data = dat, kernel = "linear", scale = FALSE)
print(svmfit)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = y ~ ., data = dat, kernel = "linear", scale = FALSE)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  linear 
##        cost:  1 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  2

Visualize the results using plot(). The points that fall on the margin and thus affect the classification line are called the support vectors.

# Plot Results
plot(svmfit, dat)

svmfit$SV # support vectors
##         x.1       x.2
## 1  0.900142 0.3644608
## 13 2.018173 1.4410811
# manually plot data and separating hyperplane
plot(x.1 ~ x.2, data = dat, col=dat$y)
cf <- coef(svmfit)
abline(-cf[1]/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "red")
# plot margin and mark support vectors
abline(-(cf[1] + 1)/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "blue")
abline(-(cf[1] - 1)/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "blue")
points(svmfit$SV[,2], svmfit$SV[,1], pch = 2, cex = 2)

In the plot, points that are represented by an “X” are the support vectors, or the points that directly affect the classification line. The points marked with an “o” are the other points, which don’t affect the calculation of the line. This principle will lay the foundation for support vector machines.

8.2 Support Vector Classifiers

Most real data sets will not be fully separable by a linear boundary. To handle such data, I must use modified methodology. I simulate a new data set where the classes are more mixed.

set.seed(2022)
d <- generate2ClassGaussian(50, 2)
d$Class <- as.factor(d$Class)

# Plot data set
ggplot(data = d, aes(x = X2, y = X1, color = Class, shape = Class)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#000000", "#FF0000")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Whether the data is separable or not, the svm command syntax is the same. In the case of data that is not linearly separable, however, the cost argument takes on real importance. This quantifies the penalty associated with having an observation on the wrong side of the classification boundary. Moreover, the kernel argument allows us to select a function based on the assumed shape of the data. For now I assume the data are linearly separable.

Use a linear kernel to fit an SVM to the model data set, with a cost of 10.

# Fit Support Vector Machine model to data set
svmfit2 <- svm(Class ~ ., data = d, kernel = "linear", cost = 10) 
# Plot Results
plot(svmfit2, d)

# manually plot data and separating hyperplane
scaled.d <- scale(d[,1:2]) # Note that we've scaled the predictors for svmfit2
plot(X1 ~ X2, data = scaled.d, col=d$Class)
cf <- coef(svmfit2)
abline(-cf[1]/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "red")

# plot margin and mark support vectors
abline(-(cf[1] + 1)/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "blue")
abline(-(cf[1] - 1)/cf[2], -cf[3]/cf[2], col = "blue")
points(svmfit2$SV[,2], svmfit2$SV[,1], pch = 5, cex = 2)

Then, instead of specifying a cost up front, use the tune function from e1071 to test various costs and identify which value produces the best fitting model. Use the ranges argument, which takes a list of vectors, to define the range of costs we are interested in. Utilize a cost of list(c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100)).

set.seed(2022)
# Find optimal cost of misclassification
tune.out <- tune(svm, Class ~ ., data = d, kernel = "linear",
                 ranges = list(cost = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100)))

# Extract the best model
bestmod <- tune.out$best.model
print(bestmod)
## 
## Call:

8.3 Support Vector Machines (Nonlinear)

Support Vector Classifiers are a subset of the group of classification structures known as Support Vector Machines. Support Vector Machines can construct classification boundaries that are nonlinear in shape. The options for classification structures using the svm command from the e1071 package are linear, polynomial, radial, and sigmoid. To demonstrate a nonlinear classification boundary, I will construct a new data set.

# Construct larger random data set
set.seed(2022)
d <- generateABA(200, 2, var = 0.15)
d$Class <- as.factor(d$Class)

# Plot data
ggplot(data = d, aes(x = X2, y = X1, color = Class, shape = Class)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#000000", "#FF0000")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Notice that the data is not linearly separable, and furthermore, isn’t all clustered together in a single group. There are two sections of class 1 observations with a cluster of class 2 observations in between.

To demonstrate the power of SVMs, take 100 random observations from the set and use this train data to construct the boundary. Set kernel = "radial" based on the shape of our data and plot the results.

# Set pseudorandom number generator
set.seed(2022)

# Sample training data and fit model
train <- base::sample(200, 100, replace = FALSE)
train <- train[order(train)]

svmfit3 <- svm(Class ~ ., data = d[train,], kernel = "radial", gamma = 1, cost = 10)

# Plot classifier
plot(svmfit3, d)

I see that, at least visually, the SVM does a reasonable job of separating the two classes. To fit the model, I used cost = 10, but as mentioned previously, it isn’t usually obvious which cost will produce the optimal classification boundary. Then, I can use the tune command to try several different values of cost as well as several different values of gamma, a scaling parameter used to fit nonlinear boundaries.

Again, use the tune function from e1071 and the train data to test various costs and gamma, a scaling parameter used to fit nonlinear boundaries.

set.seed(2022)
# Tune model to find optimal cost, gamma values
tune.out <- tune(svm, Class ~ ., data = d[train,], kernel = "radial",
                 ranges = list(cost = c(0.1,1,10,20,50,100), # A list of parameter vectors for cost
                 gamma = c(0.5,1,2,3,4)))

# Show best model
tune.out$best.model

{

9 Clustering and PCA

This exercise performs model-based clustering and PCA.

library(tidyverse)
library(MASS) # for mvrnorm
library(mclust) # clustering

9.1 Model-based Clustering

The most popular clustering approach is the Gaussian mixture model (GMM) where each observation is assumed to be distributed as one of \(k\) multivariate-normal distributions, where \(k\) is the number of clusters.

GMMs are founded on the multivariate normal (Gaussian) distribution where \(p\) variables are assumed to have means and a covariance matrix, which describes the joint variability (i.e., covariance) between each pair of variables. GMMs assume the clusters can be created using \(k\) such Gaussian distributions.

First, let’s generate synthetic datasets.

set.seed(123)
# three sets of random correlated variables (that is, clusters)
# cluster 1
mu1 <- c(2, 3)
Sigma1 <- matrix(c(1, 0.8, 0.8, 1), ncol = 2)
cluster1 <- mvrnorm(n = 50, mu = mu1, Sigma = Sigma1)

# cluster 2
mu2 <- c(-2, -2)
Sigma2 <- matrix(c(1, -0.4, -0.4, 1), ncol = 2)
cluster2 <- mvrnorm(n = 50, mu = mu2, Sigma = Sigma2)

# cluster 3
mu3 <- c(3, -2)
Sigma3 <- matrix(c(1, 0.1, 0.1, 1), ncol = 2)
cluster3 <- mvrnorm(n = 50, mu = mu3, Sigma = Sigma3)

data1 <- rbind(cluster1, cluster2, cluster3)

Create another scatterplot with different shape/color for each cluster. Note that this shows you the true cluster I would like to estimate using GMM.

# standardize the variables
data1 <- scale(data1)

# a separate data frame with cluster labels
data1_labeled <- as.data.frame(data1)
data1_labeled$cluster <- c(rep("a", 50), rep("b", 50), rep("c", 50))

# scatterplot with labels
ggplot(data1_labeled, aes(V1, V2, color = cluster, shape = cluster)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw()

The covariance matrix describes the geometry of the clusters; namely, the volume, shape, and orientation of the clusters. GMMs allow for flexible clustering structures by adding constraints to the covariance matrix. These constraints can be one or more of the following:

  • volume: each cluster has approximately the same number of observations;
  • shape: each cluster has approximately the same variance so that the distribution is spherical;
  • orientation: each cluster is forced to be axis-aligned.

Mclust function from mclust package fit models with different \(\Sigma\) types and different number of clusters (\(k\)) by EM algorithm, and then select the best model using a selection criteria such as BIC.

# fit GMM
set.seed(123)
clustering1 <- Mclust(data1)
summary(clustering1)
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## Gaussian finite mixture model fitted by EM algorithm 
## ---------------------------------------------------- 
## 
## Mclust VVE (ellipsoidal, equal orientation) model with 3 components: 
## 
##  log-likelihood   n df       BIC       ICL
##       -276.9643 150 15 -629.0881 -629.5875
## 
## Clustering table:
##  1  2  3 
## 50 50 50

Visualize the performance of different models using BIC. Compare different models and briefly explain the best model.

# model selection based on BIC
plot(clustering1, what = "BIC")

Create a contingency table with true clusters and estimates from the best fitted model. Visualize the clusters of the best fitted model.

# compare to actual classes
table(clustering1$classification, data1_labeled$cluster)
##    
##      a  b  c
##   1 50  0  0
##   2  0 50  0
##   3  0  0 50
# how the best model classifies observations
plot(clustering1, what = "classification")

One of the advantages of using GMM for clustering lies in its use of probability and measure of uncertainty.

Draw an uncertainty plot where it visualizes the observations with high uncertainty (low probability) in its cluster assignment as larger points.

# estimated uncertainty of classification
plot(clustering1, what = "uncertainty")

In the uncertainty plot, I notice the observations near the center of the densities are small, indicating small uncertainty (or high probability) of being from that respective component.

# the observation with maximum uncertainty
round(max(clustering1$uncertainty), 3)
## [1] 0.086
# estimated probability of belonging to a particular cluster
round(clustering1$z[which.max(clustering1$uncertainty),], 3)
## [1] 0.000 0.914 0.086

So far, I did not specify \(k\) but used the default values of G = 1:9 to fit the models for each value and find the best model.

Fit GMM with G = 2:20 and visualize its BIC and classification result of the best fitted model as before.

set.seed(123)
# can specify the number of clusters (default is 1 to 9)
clustering2 <- Mclust(data1, G = 2:20)
plot(clustering2, what = "BIC")

plot(clustering2, what = "classification")

9.3 PCA

The second part of this exercise will be a brief demonstration of principle component analysis. I use PCA to explore and visualize the scored whiskey datasets that you can access from here.

The data consists of 86 whiskey brands and 12 features about scores on taste including sweetness, smoky, nutty etc.

First load the data.

rm(list=ls())
whiskey <- read.csv("data/whisky.csv")[, c(-1, -2, -15:-17)]

9.4 Computing PCA

I use the prcomp function to conduct PCA.

Use prcomp to compute the principle components of the standardized data.

# compute PCA
pca1 <- prcomp(whiskey, scale=TRUE, center = TRUE)

The summary method describes the importance of the PCs. The first row describes the standard deviation (i.e., the square roots of the eigenvalue) associated with each PC. Larger numbers means this component is more “interesting” or “important” in the sense that it captures more variation.

The second row shows the proportion of the variance in the data explained by each component while the third row describe the cumulative proportion of explained variance.

Print summary() of your pca object and observe the result.

summary(pca1)
## Importance of components:

## Proportion of Variance 0.2698 0.1594 0.1003 0.08641 0.07985 0.06996 0.06532
## Cumulative Proportion  0.2698 0.4291 0.5294 0.61579 0.69564 0.76560 0.83092
##                            PC8     PC9   PC10   PC11    PC12
## Standard deviation     0.80493 0.68547 0.6312 0.5288 0.48291
## Proportion of Variance 0.05399 0.03916 0.0332 0.0233 0.01943
## Cumulative Proportion  0.88491 0.92406 0.9573 0.9806 1.00000

I can see there that the first two PCs accounts for about 43% of the variance of the data.

9.5 Visualizing PCA

I can call plot on our PCA object, which returns a scree plot of the variances (y-axis) associated with the PCs (x-axis). Create a scree plot to decide how many PCs to retain for further analysis.

# scree plot
plot(pca1, type="l",main="Number of Components v. Variance Explained")

A scree plot shows the eigenvalues or PVE for each individual PC. Most scree plots look broadly similar in shape, starting high on the left, falling rather quickly, and then flattening out at some point. This is because the first component usually explains much of the variability, the next few components explain a moderate amount, and the latter components only explain a small fraction of the overall variability. The scree plot criterion looks for the “elbow” in the curve and selects all components just before the line flattens out, which looks like three in our example.

Run biplot funcion with the pca object to visualize both PC loadings and scores.

# biplot
biplot(pca1)

The ggfortify package lets ggplot2 know how to interpret PCA objects. After installing and loading ggfortify, run the autoplot function with your pca object.

library(ggfortify)

autoplot(pca1)

Passing shape = FALSE makes plot with labels instead of points.

autoplot(pca1, shape = F)

Plot loadings with loadings = TRUE

autoplot(pca1, shape = F,
         loadings = T,
         loadings.label = T)
